metadata.name: Saccharin #74
metadata.description:
A continuation of my previous work but with a more minimalistic visual approach. Randomly generated primitive geometry are rendered as texture that undergoes a series of nodes to create a grayscale image. The texture is then colored with gradient map, layered with pixel noise to divide it into a randomly sized grid then subtly blurred in some areas to create a dreamy effect.

The resulting visual can seem vaguely familiar but at the same time can not be pinpointed to a specific time and place identity; it can vary between a Futurist painting look-alike to resembling an early 2000s colorful news bumper. Hazy memory slowly and constantly shifting, clouded vision taste artificially sweet, sometimes with a metallic aftertaste.

Just like saccharin.

----------
Press 'S' to capture a 3840x3840 screenshot of the current frame.
⚠️ Can be GPU extensive! ⚠️

XALTED 2022

metadata.name: ZOOM (4hwf) #75
metadata.description:
"Das System lässt keine Überraschung zu. Überraschung ist Ausdruck partieller Unkenntnis. Überraschung weist auf Mangel von Wissen hin, deutet Leerstellen an. Bisher hatten sie keine Leerstellen festgestellt." — Herbert W. Franke

ZOOM explores linear scaling of pixels by zooming into a noisy framebuffer. Various zoom levels are composed one below the other, becoming a cinematic animation through iteration of the hue values of the pixels in the framebuffer.

In Gedenken an Herbert W. Franke
Kim Asendorf, 2022

metadata.name: one hour #86
metadata.description:
`one hour` is an interactive installation exploring the bond between humans and computers, inviting you to pause and share a meditative moment with an algorithmic stranger.

Rather than conventionally interacting with the piece, lower your guard and allow it to interact with you through an intimately human connection - a heart beat. `one hour` follows this heart as it beats through an hour of its enduring existence, captured by an EKG divided into 60 rows of 60 seconds each. Stylistically, it emulates realistic paper and ink using custom texture and line renderers. The piece will play through the duration of the hour, pause for five minutes, then begin anew.

`one hour` was created for a physical installation, projected to a wall and animated in real time. By default it will render at high speed to reveal the preview. For the most immersive experience at home, it should be viewed in full screen and adjusted to real time speed (controlled via the number keys).

||| controls

[s] save as png
[r] reset animation
[l] toggle looping [default on]
[1-5] adjust render speed
[--1] real time (1 hour) [recommended]
[--2] 6x (10 minutes)
[--3] 60x (1 minute)
[--4] 300x (12 seconds) [default]
[--5] full speed

metadata.name: Sand Table #99
metadata.description:
Just like a sand jar that you made or played with as a child. A recreation of layered colored sand with star glitter at the "peaks." Rare versions will be all gold and super rare has rainbow shimmer glitter.

Press 's' to take a screenshot. The image size is 1000x1000. 

Features
- 20 color palettes
- 2 color distribution methods
- 4 sand distribution methods
- sand size variation
- noise variables to determine patterns and layers

Rare features
- color sand with gold stars
- all stars instead of sand grains
- all gold glitter with silver stars
- all rainbow glitter with silver stars (super rare)

metadata.name: Sixty# #34
metadata.description:
This idea was born from recent discussion on generative art and the path the medium is finding for itself. The project aims to take aesthetic concepts from sci fi graphic novels and blend them with generative systems of abstraction. 

The debate is between using previously established art forms to influence this new medium, or using a new medium to meticulously reproduce a previous medium. I believe there’s room to explore the full spectrum, and I am attempting to find the midpoint that fits my work and brings me the most happiness.

The title describes the eventual aesthetic objective, which is to create a piece which might look like a splash page a colorist alone has been given the freedom to design and explore their own specialty. It explores centralized polar compositions, vibrant colors, plus lots and lots of movement. 60# paper is a standard weight for printing of comic books and graphic novels.

Press ’s’ in live view to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: anaglyphic - Moka #12
metadata.description:
Industrial design has taken many forms in the past decades, and some of them have endured. The manual of mass-produced technical products have kept on featuring pseudo-technical diagrams of your most recent purchase. But for now, you will ignore it and assume that its use will be intuitive enough for you to manage. Only when you have a problem with it will you explore this little piece of literature, and discover that you've been doing it wrong all along.

This moka piece is a mix of different cultural perspectives on the service manual exercise. The moka pot's European orientalist origin is blended with the idiomatic Swedish brand naming shenanigans and the 80s Japanese service manual schematics aesthetics.

metadata.name: Copenhagen Interpretation #44
metadata.description:
The Copenhagen Interpretation of quantum physics suggests that objects don't have physical properties until being observed.

In this generative piece by itsgalo and Spøgelsesmaskinen, a set of objects are being held in "superposition" and finally positioned when observed and minted.

Use mouse/touch to zoom, pan, and rotate. Press 's' to grab a screenshot. Best viewed in Firefox.

metadata.name: Fast Food Wall Art Simulation #56
metadata.description:
"Fast Food Wall Art Simulation" is created from many hidden circular drawings. 

I placed each drawing in a different hidden canvas and read its pixel values to approximate the texture of the circles. Technically that makes this an Image composition, but the images are never shown on the canvas.

I played around with different ways the circles could be overlapped. Differing opacity, blend modes, and pixel skipping were used to create some interesting textures.

In my testing, many of the renders, especially the more earth-tone ones, reminded me of art used in fast food restaurants in the 90s when I was growing up.

Features:
Four different sizes: 9x16, 11x14", 12x18", 12x12"
Portrait or landscape orientation
~500 color pallets, one black and white, one CMYK, one RGB, and the rest from Jam3/nice-color-palettes.

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

License: CC-BY

Please find me on Twitter and Instagram at @natenolting.

metadata.name: Mines #17
metadata.description:
"He found himself wondering at times, especially in the autumn, about the wild lands, and strange visions of mountains that he had never seen came into his dreams"
- J.R.R. Tolkien

Mines is an exploration of these mountains of dreams, and the ancient mechanics that shape them. The work of eons, where the landscapes we know rise and fall like ocean waves.

To know them, we must go beneath the mountain.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press “s” to save png
- Use param ?width=x to render at specific width
- Use param ?bg=true to render on full color background (instead of the default dark background)

metadata.name: ARAUCO #92
metadata.description:
The Araucaria Araucana, also known as pewén, is a sacred tree for the Mapuche and an emblem of Chile. With an origin dating back 260 million years to the Triassic period, it is part of the oldest forests on the planet. These ancient trees are endangered due to logging, forest fires, and grazing.

ARAUCO is a tribute to araucarias and Mapuche iconography. Incorporating elements such as the Kultrung, the Wünelfe star, and the staggered cross Ngümin, the work displays a typical landscape of southern Chile with the Andes Mountains in the background and the native forest. 

–

Press 's' to export a 4960x7016 PNG file suitable for A2 printing at 300 dpi.

Made with p5js.

Patricio Isaías, September 2022

CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 License
